{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492649","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492649"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:39:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:39:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1120"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1120"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.44,0.29,0.16,0.08,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1120"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103569"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1120","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1120"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1120"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85986"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"377"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7915"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8562"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8944"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36564"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36820"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103569","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103569"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 22-year-old woman is referred to a breast clinic with a two-week history of what she describes as a painless swelling in her left breast. She has never had any previous breast problems, nor any family history of breast disease. On examination she has Cup C-sized breasts and no readily identifiable distinct mass. An ultrasound is normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is most appropriate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reassurance with no follow-up","Reassurance with six-month follow up","Reassurance with 12-month follow up","Fine needle aspiration biopsy","Core biopsy"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA recent study suggests that with a normal breast examination and normal ultrasound, patients under the age of 25 who present with various breast symptoms (perceived lump, pain, nipple discharge) and no genetic susceptibility can be provided\u003Cstrong\u003E reassurance with no follow-up\u003C/strong\u003E needed. Naturally, the patient\u0027s anxiety -or her confidence - will guide the doctor\u0027s advice as to what further guidance should be offered. The patient needs to be reassured that it is very unlikely there is any worrying underlying explanation for her symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReassurance with six-month follow up \u003C/strong\u003Eis inappropriate as breast cancer is rare in this age group (incidence of 3.2 cases per million) and would be an ineffective use of resources and time. This answer is therefore incorrect. The patient can be reassured that there is unlikely to be any sinister pathology, however, whilst not necessary, it is always practical to provide the option to return in six months should her symptoms persist, so a further clinical examination plus any imaging can be repeated\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Ereassurance with 12-month follow up \u003C/strong\u003Eis an inappropriate plan of management and would be over-cautious treatment of this woman. However, depending on her level of anxiety, this form of follow-up could be arranged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Eis a part of the gold-standard triple assessment but given this patient\u0027s extremely low risk, it is unnecessarily invasive and expensive and can be safely omitted. This would be done if there was a clearly identifiable mass.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimilarly, \u003Cstrong\u003Ecore biopsy \u003C/strong\u003Ewould be unnecessarily invasive and expensive and with this patient\u0027s risk profile, can be safely omitted. A core biopsy would be impractical without a mass to target.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Women under 25 with breast symptoms, with a normal breast examination and/or ultrasonography can be spared a biopsy provided there is no genetic susceptibility"],"references":["Yue D, Swinson C, Ravichandran D. Triple assessment is not necessary in most young women referred with breast symptoms. Ann R Coll Surg Engl 2015; 97:466-68."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1120"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85986"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-23T20:39:54+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-23T20:40:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1120"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103569"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}}